[{"sha":"ed27d28820e9c29fe25f71a46ee01ee66795fbc8","author":{"email":"f4c36f5cc29186f0c6182c6b025276fa1312e8ab@google.com","name":"Matthias Kramm"},"message":"Only use sharding inference if we're not falling back to maximal sharding.

The TpuShardingIdentification pass might run sharding identification twice,
if, during the first pass, it found a maximal sharding (or no sharding.)
In the second pass, we want to fall back to maximal sharding, so don't
try to infer the sharding from the computation.

Also, merge all the tpu_sharding_identication*mlir tests back into one file.
